In it, bitcoin was described as “the most successful virtual currency”, “competitive with the dollar or the euro” and “similar to conventional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other systems with virtual currency types such as “credits”, used to advance a video game and which can be won by playing or bought (and even occasionally redeemed).
The social network Facebook also developed this type of system.
But in every exchange a central authority controls and deals with changes.
With bitcoin, all network nodes are both depository of ledgers, verifiers, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually made between two electronic addresses in the form of email.
A user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information linked to this transaction is electronically signed through a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that bitcoin changes are contained in the public ledger, which is disseminated throughout the network.
The key milestone is to write that new transaction in that book.
This goes through the resolution of a mathematical challenge launched to computers and the winner, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding that complementary line.
This is a phase of file cutting, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique numerical footprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "cutting" the set.
The goal is to find the number that offers a particular footprint (more zeros at first).
Once that number is found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructiblely linked to the chain of sets of the other transactions; any modification would change the footprint.
If, to commit a fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (in less than ten minutes), the network would only accept as valid one of the two transactions; the other would remain orphaned, since both have different footprints.
The computer that solves the challenge takes 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, that reward is split in two regularly, likely before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving a wide margin.
The difficulty of this challenge is also revealed in each increase in computing power.
The life of the network already has its ups and downs.
Websites that offer services for Bitcoin have been attacked and bitcoins have been stolen in deposit.
“The failure used does not affect the same protocol,” says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also takes into account the potential for money laundering thanks to this anonymous service.
But cash has the same flaw.
Major players like Wikipedia reject such payments.
Others, such as the WordPress platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the ledger and showed that about 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, the “giant sales” were launched.
“They changed $30,000,” rejoices Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, author of a pedagogical book on this currency, believes strongly in the potential of this technology in addition to the network of transactions.
Its system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which are thus cheaper.
The bearer, in addition, manages his identity and can therefore remain anonymous.
The system is easy to start up in stores, which do not have to install new terminals or software.
They just need to provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who claims to have thousands of users.
There is a general movement of revision of hierarchical systems by more horizontal systems.
“It will take a while for Bitcoin to prevail, but in 2013 there could be a change,” he predicts.
In its report, the ECB also plans to re-evaluate the various risks, which are now considered high, should this currency succeed.
