Is an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in another way?
As far as the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Auditors) operates there, with an organization similar to ours, with a college as well, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The competences are also somewhat analogous, however, while Germany has a federal organisation, the courts of account are even at this level.
The Federal Court of Auditors (BRH) can only control federal money, what we here call state funds.
The public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities there, in Germany, are controlled by the Federal Court of Auditors.
As for local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data, but Germany remains a model in some respects, but it cannot be specified exactly what is best.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of the inspectors?
Surely not, but, I repeat, I do not like to make such comparisons.
It is necessary to say that even those countries that we take as a model must face a large number of problems.
If it weren't, they wouldn't benefit from collaborating with our office, would they?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment to the law on public procurement mean for your Office?
Given that the validity period of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, we need to have a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparation of the future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are corrected and the like.
Do you consider that the passage of this law is beneficial, or rather that it constitutes a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulation "hardens" and that it is impossible to comply with it.
Already under the previous legislation, the persons controlled were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant a violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create greater bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path begins.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDG would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, referring to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA1>varc system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way, and if it forbids anything, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the Office from performing such checks and demanding obligations.
You can say, “We change the law and allow it,” but you can’t say that we’ll do as if nothing.
In the law on public procurement, the rules are quite strict as to how one should act formally, and that is how it should be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic to exclude the candidate with the best offer for not meeting formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
