Next year we would also like to play at the Bohemian National Hall in New York and I personally, taking advantage of the fact that we are in America, would like to complete it with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your plans abroad are not exactly minimalist, so far you have performed for example in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How is the logistics and organization of these trips?
It’s not as difficult as it may seem at first glance.
There are five members in an electric wheelchair, the chairs must travel in the luggage compartment and we also carry a lot of weight, the boxes with the instruments...
However, so far we have managed well. <0xC4><0x8C>SA and British Airways were perfectly prepared, which does not stop surprising me.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned from, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to the trips abroad you can compare the different attitudes of society towards the disabled and other aspects.
What have you met so far?
In Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities, everything works better than here; in Russia we have witnessed that in the east there is still a long way to go.
Unlike Prague, Moscow is full of barriers, where it is still uncommon for a person to travel alone through the city center in an electric wheelchair.
