Argo Movie: If it gets raw, call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Réza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the United States, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration the situation offered no positive prospect: throwing the shah overboard could not be allowed, since if it did, it would jeopardize the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the U.S., his fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck themes an episode of this story, which reaped a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, to do so a covert story helped an extravagant point: they went out with Canadian passports, as members of the film team examining the location in the country for the filming of a science fiction superproduction.
Combination of genders
The plan outlined by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood’s collaboration.
To make the lie seem true, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production society even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a unique combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other hand, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example may be the series Ocean's Eleven).
The film combines the moods. On the one hand, we find well-documented sequences of Tehran. The sequence of credits shows emblematic photographs of the time of events, which were embodied in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other hand, typical Hollywood scenes a bit lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And moreover, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: dressed men who analyze the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the subject of mockery, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Goodbye Little, Goodbye" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is the first Affleck film in which the action does not take place in the city of Boston, where he grew up.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed directors of ancient films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran is "wheeled" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the takeover of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic capacity that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of confusion and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect on the fictional scenes (the impostor team at the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story does not offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes he adds something to the reality: here it doesn’t all come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis lurks at the Tehran airport, the diversion of a call to America and the unbridled search behind his runway become madness).
Argo’s weakness is the out of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are not the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of dramatic trace, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, valuing its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But if it collapses, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real story and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
