Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs of viral origin are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Slashes and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups of those affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are most common in men who have sex with other men.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, at least four out of every five cases of syphilis in Germany originate from sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV infection among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, about 20 per cent of new HIV infections are recorded in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papillomavirus is also added to the most common diseases among young people.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, approximately 2,700 cases were recorded.
This is one-tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, discomfort with urination, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or cause other symptoms and are therefore not detected.
How can one be protected?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through dirt infections and physical contact.
For this reason, experts recommend undergoing regular medical examinations, especially if you frequently change sexual partners.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
