Bradley Manning did not report ill-treatment, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of abuse of Bradley Manning during his time in prison
The trial focuses on Manning's period at Quantico Military Prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case to be dismissed on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors tried to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while under military detention.
During an interrogation by the prosecution of Manning in a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Commander Ashden Fein stated that records of the weekly visits of officers from the unit Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about the treatment he was receiving.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence's request that the case be dismissed because his imprisonment had been harsh and that this had already entailed sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had thought of committing suicide while in detention.
The military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later posted the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of information.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein and Manning reviewed the forms officers filled in after Manning’s visits during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was imprisoned under maximum detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers allegedly asked Manning questions and jotted down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had rated the treatment given to him by the caretakers as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional."
The forms do not show any complaints of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that the officers visiting him had discussed those issues and had indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they did not record those issues in the register.
"They were writing 'no incidents' (after talking about the problems) but this doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any problems," Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining the suicide intentions she had expressed in a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to get the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he was.
The military said it had placed him under that restrictive regime, which lies one degree below that of surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of other people.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and (wanted) to stop being on injury prevention ... so I could enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered committing suicide in Kuwait and that on one occasion he lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced only to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning claimed that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, some clothes and glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light coming from outside pointing to his eyes while he was sleeping.
He said that if the guards could not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's statement that, after being forced to sleep naked in his Quantico cell for a night, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of jailers and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given a chance to cover himself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's interrogation on Friday, Manning said he deduced by the concierge's order that he should drop the blanket he could have covered with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered him to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underwear or his flip-flops to self-harm but had not.
Manning testified that that night his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
Her lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account the experiences she experienced during her time in prison and drastically reduce her sentence should she be convicted in the war council, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to make Manning guilty of misdemeanor crimes and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was detained under the rules of application to any detainee who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life imprisonment.
