Generic Tobacco Packaging Act Enters into Force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and parts of the body with diseases wear on boxes of a dull green color, which are the same for all tobacco brands
The Australian law on tobacco and generic packaging, a pioneer in the world, comes into force and replaces the logos and colors of the brands with a wrapping of an olive-green off, horrifying images of parts of the body with diseases and representations of sick children and babies because they are children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the different images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, compulsory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed on a small font type.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
Australia’s federal government says the goal is to deter young people from smoking by eliminating the traits that make this habit glamorous.
He trusts studies that show that if a person has not started smoking before the age of 26, there is a 99% chance that he will never do so.
“You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls linked the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering taking similar measures.
