Petronella Wyatt: "I was harassed until I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Tory"
Students are not attacked for their views only now
I don’t remember any moment in my life when I haven’t been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and older brother had been in what I thought was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary-era Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thinking and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue a career in history, I had already packed my bags, triggering the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and started crying.
My friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had given up because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A.N. Wilson announced jokingly that I had left because I was forced to drink in chunked cups.
The truth was less fun.
I fled from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my flamboyant name, or the fact that it came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a prominent adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative party.
You might be wondering what that's coming from now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering a similar persecution.
The institutionalized and growing hatred for Conservative Party students is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College’s JCR say they are “often seriously estranged, personally attacked, and treated as unpleasant people” for their political ideas.
They want to create a position on their college’s equal opportunity committee to make sure they can express their opinions freely.
His situation was not favored by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and portraying the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated like “Turkish heads” by introducing higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, a 20-year-old vice president of the University of Nottingham Conservative Party Association, said in a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing trend of the left in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student at Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, 19, and the president-elect of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members towards people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first weeks in Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
The hatred of the Conservative Party was at its highest.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, an alumnus, an "honoris causa" title after cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have shocked any Stalinist.
Already during the first days of the new university students welcome week, when the new students meet and meet the professors, I received a taste of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative college students, but willingly participated in it.
The policy of the miners’ strike, privatization and the government’s opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the wooden halls of the seminary.
The first one I attended had to translate French texts of the 18th century into English and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (already deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't give one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew how to expel bad bile.
"Is it that the Thatcherists refuse to learn French or are they simply fools?" he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning with the tears I was trying to contain.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your free time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt grumbled.
I returned to my room as a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college; then I felt a slight slap on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
“I’m afraid that’s how it goes.
They mess with anyone suspected of being Tory.
For me it's very complicated, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it'll be even worse.
Many newcomers to the Tories appear to be Labourers.”
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to cover up.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved useless.
A freshman in Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted that song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do the Tories have sex?" one asked.
"They beat each other up, don't they?"
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to hang out with people who thought like me only after dark?
Should I become a Labour Party and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me were presented as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only professor openly Tory was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History intended for my college.
They hated him for being not only the Conservative party, but also Thatcher’s foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote his speeches to him.
I was barely there.
He hated the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a chair at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he told me.
I began to move daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But if it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my dear dream needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude.”
His painful eyes began to cloud.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you let it go.”
Tired of so many trips to London, my emotional endurance was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of history had insinuated, totally serious, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red of shame inside, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "stupid old men."
The truce lasted a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside curled up in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I packed up and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me a weak cryer.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 Prime Ministers of the Conservative Party but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation of equality and freedom of thought.
