The hardest craft in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano are playing on life and health by loading 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone trails
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living by extracting sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulphur gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies upon contact with air.
After plucking large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle pace, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the cliff.
They know that any trash could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who took off years ago on the cliffs of the Kawah Ijen.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 cents for every kilo of sulphur they extract
Once upstairs, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly carrying the heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) for each kilo of sulphur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to manufacture matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As usual it is to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three daily ports.
It takes three hours in each and ends up ground, but allow it to collect 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is triple what I would gain in the field.
“The miners’ pay is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” explains the porter, who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, her salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the cut was not that hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as blunt as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto has been playing with his skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulphur has already begun to pay his bill despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases that the volcano releases.
This is the price you have to pay to achieve your dream.
“I’ll work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he said.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man might be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing an unclean wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater lighting up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 carriers load the sulphur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater
Despite its penguin benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulphur to save costs or supplies any equipment to the carriers, who work on their own and at both the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) per camera surcharge that, next to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” protests Madrusin, a formidable 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "as much as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, aged between 18 and 10.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and squeezes the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that leave the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering serious diseases... beyond, of course, their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pains in the knees and sores in the shoulders, which have been malformed by the weight.
By swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can only carry 50 kilos at 53.
Each day, he and his companions pull 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a goat path between the weeds.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth well, where several teeth are missing.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30, also works carrying sulphur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah Ijen.
